Peter, 

I&#39;m not as familiar with Python, but in Matlab you can most definitely set mole fractions using a vector/array.  I would be surprised if the same functionality doesn&#39;t exist in Python.

For your example, you can initialize an array X for your molefractions, and create indices that keep track of the relative positions of the relevant species, within that array.  For your example, if CH4, O2, and N2 were your only species (and if the phase output in Cantera lists them in that order), you could write the following:

initialize once:
X_gas = [0]*3
i_CH4 = 0; i_O2 = 1; i_N2 = 2;

at each evaluation:
X_gas[i_CH4] = 1.0
X_gas[i_O2] = 1/phi*(1+y/4. 0))  # phi and y are computed in my code.
X_gas[i_N2] = (1/phi*(1+y/ 4.0)*(Xn2/ Xo2))  # Xn2, Xo2 are mole fractions.

and then feed the new X_gas array into the set command.

If python doesn&#39;t support passing the molefractions in as an array, there are a couple of options.  
1) You can convert the &#39;mole&#39; variables to strings, using the str( ) function, and then concantenate the strings.  

2) More efficiently, you can convert the variables into strings and drop them into the molefraction declaration string, all in a single line:

X_gas = &#39;CH4:%f,O2:%f,N2:%f&#39; % (mole_CH4,mole_O2,mole_N2)

and then: gas.set(T=900.0, P = 1.0e5, X=X_gas)

I hope this helps,
Steven



